:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-07"}
{"id":"2004.03217","submitter":"Sergey Shemyakov","authors":"Sergey Shemyakov, Roman Chernov, Dzmitry Rumiantsau, Dierk Schleicher,\n  Simon Schmitt and Anton Shemyakov","title":"Finding polynomial roots by dynamical systems -- a case study","comments":"27 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  We investigate two well known dynamical systems that are designed to find\nroots of univariate polynomials by iteration: the methods known by Newton and\nby Ehrlich-Aberth. Both are known to have found all roots of high degree\npolynomials with good complexity. Our goal is to determine in which cases which\nof the two algorithms is more efficient. We come to the conclusion that Newton\nis faster when the polynomials are given by recursion so they can be evaluated\nin logarithmic time with respect to the degree, or when all the roots are all\nnear the boundary of their convex hull. Conversely, Ehrlich-Aberth has the\nadvantage when no fast evaluation of the polynomials is available, and when\nroots are in the interior of the convex hull of other roots.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 7 Apr 2020 09:17:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-08"}
